settings are the issue. Instead, I'll focus on ensuring that the output is in JSON format. This way, I can provide the user with useful and relevant information without unnecessary repetition.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating dependencies**\\n\\nI’m looking into the Spring IoC container contexts and wondering about including `org.junit.jupiter:junit-jupiter`. The normal TCK scaffold uses JUnit, so I’ll check the plugin. The tests import `org.junit.jupiter.api.Test` without explicitly including `junit-jupiter` in the build, so that might be provided by the TCK plugin.\\n\\nNext, there’s the consideration of adding `commons-logging`. The existing version uses `commons-logging 1.1.1`, but Spring core now uses `spring-jcl`. I'll need to inspect the Spring core dependencies in the POM for clarity.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_pF49uN0zkuApxO22jXikMciF|fc_09936ee940298e16016a29073ed1b48193b172eadce972d424", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.springframework/spring-core/7.0.0/2d7f1db783fd9e2b6130d7e115802dc36f325375/spring-core-7.0.0.pom", "limit": 80}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 858, "output": 778, "cacheRead": 29184, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 30820, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781073698568, "responseId": "resp_09936ee940298e16016a29072304e481938838c37f16d591d5"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_pF49uN0zkuApxO22jXikMciF|fc_09936ee940298e16016a29073ed1b48193b172eadce972d424", "toolName": "read", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "ENOENT: no such file or directory, access '/home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.springframework/spring-core/7.0.0/2d7f1db783fd9e2b6130d7e115802dc36f325375/spring-core-7.0.0.pom'"}], "details": {}, "isError": true, "timestamp": 1781073727158}]}
